Introduction

This is an R Markdown document. Markdown is a simple formatting syntax for authoring HTML, PDF, and MS Word documents. R Markdown files permit you to interweave R code with ordinary text to produce well-formatted data analysis reports that are easy to modify. The R Markdown file itself shows the readers exactly how you got the results in your report. For more details on using R Markdown see http://rmarkdown.rstudio.com.

When you click the Knit button a document will be generated that includes both content as well as the output of any embedded R code chunks within the document. Inline R code: for the build-in R dataset cars, there were 50 cars studied. You can embed an R code chunk like this:

summary(cars)

Exercise 2

2.1 T-test

Below we perform a one sample t-test for the artificial date (that we generated ourselves).

mu=0.2
x=rnorm(100,mu,1) # creating artificial data
t.test(x,mean=0)   # t.test(x,alternative=c("two.sided"),conf.level=0.95,mu=10)
## 
##  One Sample t-test
## 
## data:  x
## t = 0.85501, df = 99, p-value = 0.3946
## alternative hypothesis: true mean is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -0.1146564  0.2882868
## sample estimates:
## mean of x 
## 0.0868152

Of course, we often do not need to report the whole output of R-commands, only certain values of the output. For example, below we perform a two-smaple t-test and report only the value of t-statistics and the p-pavue.

mu=0;nu=0.5
x=rnorm(50,mu,1); y=rnorm(50,nu,1) # creating artificial data
ttest=t.test(x,y)

The value of t-statistics in the above evaluation is -2.72 and the p-value is 0.0078.
